-{"id":"bd-kf83x","title":"WASM 2.3: Implement database export/import (Uint8Array serialization of in-memory database)","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-02T04:18:56.623023394Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-02T04:20:04.277227942Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-kf83x","depends_on_id":"bd-35lpy","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T21:54:24Z","created_by":"import","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":1807,"issue_id":"bd-kf83x","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"# Task 2.3: Database Export/Import

## What
Implement the ability to export an in-memory database as a Uint8Array (binary blob) and import from one. This is essential for persistence — the database can be serialized to IndexedDB, OPFS, or downloaded.

## API
```typescript
// Export the entire database as a binary file
const data: Uint8Array = db.export();

// Import from binary
const db = FrankenDB.import(data);

// Or: save/load convenience methods
await db.save("my-database");  // saves to OPFS or IndexedDB
const db = await FrankenDB.load("my-database");
```

## Implementation Strategy
The export format should be standard SQLite database format (100-byte header + B-tree pages). This ensures:
1. Compatibility with C SQLite tools
2. Ability to share databases between server (native) and browser (wasm)
3. Import of existing .sqlite files

### Export
- Walk all pages from page 1 to N
- Concatenate into a single Uint8Array
- Include the standard SQLite 100-byte header

### Import
- Parse the header to get page size, page count
- Create MemoryVfs with pre-populated pages
- Open Connection on the pre-populated VFS

## Acceptance Criteria
- Round-trip: create DB → insert data → export → import → query returns same data
- Standard SQLite format: exported file readable by sqlite3 CLI
- Import of externally-created .sqlite files works
- Large databases (>10MB) handled efficiently (no excessive copying)
